objects.name: wishful woodchuck
objects.description: A non-persistent Windows keylogger that logs keystrokes to a file on disk named msimm.dat. It uses Windows API calls to hook the keyboard and the log file is XOR-encoded with a multi-byte key embedded in the binary. It contains no persistence or communications functionality. Some capabilities, such as XOR 0x55 obfuscation of function names and use of the TVer versioning string, have been previously observed in use by Turla.

objects.name: msvrt.exe
objects.description: A Windows executable file that functions as a dropper for the Wishful Woodchuck keylogger DLL. It drops the DLL, stored as a resource, to a statically configured filename and calls its exported functions.

objects.name: lmm32.dll
objects.description: A 32-bit Windows DLL variant of Wishful Woodchuck, dropped by msvrt.exe. It provides its keylogging functionality using exported functions.

objects.name: hlpapi.dll
objects.description: A 32-bit Windows DLL variant of Wishful Woodchuck that does not export any functions. The analysis in the report is primarily based on this file.

objects.name: manualmap_injector.exe
objects.description: A 64-bit Windows DLL variant of Wishful Woodchuck that does not export any functions.

objects.name: Turla
objects.description: A threat group associated with the Wishful Woodchuck keylogger. The report suggests this attribution based on the use of the TVer versioning string in the log file and the encoding of Windows API function names with XOR 0x55, both of which are techniques previously observed in Turla binaries.

objects.name: Input Capture: Keylogging
objects.description: Wishful Woodchuck uses Windows API calls to log keystrokes

objects.name: Obfuscated Files or Information
objects.description: Wishful Woodchuck uses multi-byte XOR obfuscation of strings in its binary and log file

objects.name: Obfuscated Files or Information
objects.description: Wishful Woodchuck dynamically resolves Windows API functions using names XORed with 0x55

objects.name: Masquerading: Match Legitimate Name or Location
objects.description: Wishful Woodchuck uses a filename (lmm32.dll) similar to a legitimate Windows signed binary (imm32.dll)

objects.name: wishfulwoodchuck_hardcoded_xorkey
objects.description: YARA rule to detect related activity.
objects.pattern:
rule wishfulwoodchuck_hardcoded_xorkey
{
    meta:
        author = "NCSC"
        description = "Finds binaries containing the hardcoded XOR key
from the keylogger binaries"

    strings:
        $xorkey = {0A 19 59 2D 6C 59 6F FA 8B 6F 9B FF 37 9B BD 7B 59 4B
7B DD 0F 64 91 C7 D6 9C 6F 7B 9C 01 9C 91 79 C7 C8 C9 DF E1 FA FF 04 08
59 E6 64 6D 37 9B 38 81 2D 81 65 7D 66 9A}

    condition:

uint16(0) == 0x5A4D and
uint32(uint32(0x3c)) == 0x00004550 and
all of them

}

objects.description: YARA rule to detect related activity.
objects.pattern:
rule wishfulwoodchuck_file_description
{
    meta:
        author = "NCSC"
        description = "Unique file description"

strings:

$description = "Multi-User Windows IMM32 API CIient DLL" wide

condition:

uint16(0) == 0x5A4D and
uint32(uint32(0x3c)) == 0x00004550 and
all of them

}

objects.name: wishfulwoodchuck_logfile_encodedheader
objects.description: YARA rule to detect related activity.
objects.pattern:
rule wishfulwoodchuck_logfile_encodedheader
{
    meta:
        author = "NCSC"
        description = "Encoded log file header"

    strings:
        $header = {41 19 0A 2D 20 59 5F FA 81 6F CF FF 61 9B D8 7B 2B 4B
46}
    condition:
        all of them
}
